Q" style=3D"border: none !important;vertical-align: middle;-ms-interpolatio=
n-mode: bicubic;max-width: 100%;height: auto;margin: 0 auto;display: block;=
width: 100%;"></a><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-=
height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Upon reaching India&#8217;s shores, ou=
r packet is shot to a local data center to go through the digital equivalen=
t of customs. The data center&#8217;s routers check the packet&#8217;s IP a=
ddress to figure out where to send it next, through India&#8217;s domestic =
internet infrastructure, on to the ISP of its destination. These days, chan=
ces are that&#8217;s </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/df9e13=
2c-8ef7-4649-94a3-7626b32b54cc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);text-decorat=
ion: underline;">Jio</a><span>, which offers both fiber and wireless connec=
tion.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-he=
ight: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Less than a decade old and boasting a 52% Indi=
an ISP market share, Jio stands as a testament to the idea that although ma=
ny of us take internet access for granted, better internet infrastructure r=
emains a work in progress. Expected to IPO this year at a market cap of aro=
und &#8377;10 lakh crores ($120 billion), it is a testament to the massive =
value that building better internet infrastructure can create.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16=
px;">But our packet cares nothing for IPOs or rupees. It&#8217;s almost hom=
e. It makes the final sprint over Jio fiber to the local network of the per=
son on the other end of the Zoom.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: =
rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">At last, after a journey =
of about 200 milliseconds (an eternity in packet time, but less than the bl=
ink of a human eye), our packet arrives at its destination and makes the or=
iginal local network journey in reverse: switch to access point to radio si=
gnal then over WiFi to the computer.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;colo=
r: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Today, in India, our p=
acket likely travels across Cisco hardware. One day, it may be Meter&#8217;=
s.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px=
;font-size: 16px;">Finally, our packet begins to disappear.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"=
>The receiving computer's NIC greets it and strips away its Ethernet frame.=
 Its operating system peels off the IP header, then passes the UDP datagram=
 up to the application layer, where Zoom's software awaits.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"=
>Here, our packet is reunited with its siblings &#8211; other packets that =
took different routes but arrived in the same place within milliseconds. Zo=
om reassembles them in the correct order, using the sequence numbers in the=
ir RTP headers like a jigsaw puzzle guide.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px =
0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Finally, the dat=
a our packet carried is decoded, decompressed, and converted back into audi=
o and video signals. The recipient's speakers vibrate, their screen flicker=
s, and voila! Your awkward interjection is heard and seen, as if by magic, =
on the other side of the world.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rg=
b(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Our packet's job is done. I=
n less time than it took you to read "Sorry.. yes &#8230;", it traveled hal=
fway around the world, bringing a tiny piece of your presence along with it=
=2E And as you continue your Zoom call,=
 countless more packets embark on the=20=
same journey, in a never ending cycle of birth, light-speed travel, and dec=
omposition.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-hei=
ght: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>This is the way the world works now, and =
the way the Varanasi brothers bet the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/d64ae1fa-4b7e-4492-9133-b3ff2099dfa9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54,55=
,55);text-decoration: underline;">world will work more and more in the futu=
re</a><span>, in the same way that Metcalfe and Krause bet that an exponent=
ial curve would continue to run until they could connect all computers in l=
ocal networks that in turn connected to wider networks that have connected =
the world.</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);li=
ne-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">So among all of the many things that the =
Varanasis could be doing, they chose to move packets, for three reasons:</p=
><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0;padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;=
"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-s=
izing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><strong>The=
 internet is phenomenal and there&#8217;s merit to making it great.</strong=
></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,=
55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left:=
 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><strong>Everything is packets.</strong></p=
></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,55,55);=
line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px=
;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><strong>We all will use the internet, and pack=
ets, more than we currently do.</strong></p></li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>&#=
8220;This call right now is packets,&#8221; Anil told me. &#8220;When you o=
rder an Uber, send an email, it&#8217;s packets. The money in your bank is =
packets. </span><strong>Everything is just packets moving left to right. Th=
at&#8217;s it. That&#8217;s the world.</strong><span>&#8221;</span></p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size=
